WEBVTT

00:01.533 --> 00:02.800
♪ ♪

00:02.800 --> 00:03.866
TOM:
We await the arrival
of Colonel Lennox

00:03.866 --> 00:05.266
and his company.

00:05.266 --> 00:06.300
ALISON:
Will your family

00:06.300 --> 00:07.633
be joining you, Colonel?

00:07.633 --> 00:08.833
I have no such attachments.

00:08.833 --> 00:10.000
♪ ♪

00:10.000 --> 00:11.133
CHARLES:
Miss Lambe, I must confess

00:11.133 --> 00:12.766
I noticed you
in the Assembly Rooms yesterday.

00:12.766 --> 00:15.033
I wonder what it was
that caught your attention.

00:15.033 --> 00:17.566
I want to give
my husband a child.

00:17.566 --> 00:18.866
CHARLOTTE:
As I am resolved not to marry,

00:18.866 --> 00:20.600
I will need an income.

00:20.600 --> 00:21.766
ALISON:
A governess?

00:21.766 --> 00:23.333
MARY:
For Mr. Colbourne,
of all people?

00:23.333 --> 00:24.900
COLBOURNE:
The position is yours.

00:24.900 --> 00:26.233
You start on Monday.

00:26.233 --> 00:29.966
♪ ♪

00:31.333 --> 00:37.100
♪ ♪

00:41.166 --> 00:45.466
♪ ♪

00:51.266 --> 00:54.833
♪ ♪

00:57.400 --> 01:02.600
♪ ♪

01:26.066 --> 01:29.166
(horses approaching,
seagulls cawing)

01:29.166 --> 01:35.400
♪ ♪

01:35.400 --> 01:37.700
LENNOX:
Miss Heywood.

01:37.700 --> 01:38.833
Colonel Lennox.

01:41.600 --> 01:43.066
Forgive me.

01:43.066 --> 01:45.133
The other day
I spoke rashly.

01:45.133 --> 01:46.333
You were honest.

01:46.333 --> 01:48.100
It was refreshing.

01:48.100 --> 01:50.200
Would that every young woman
spoke with such candor.

01:50.200 --> 01:51.233
Thank you, Colonel.

01:51.233 --> 01:53.166
But you'll have to excuse me.

01:53.166 --> 01:55.100
You have an appointment?
I have a job,

01:55.100 --> 01:56.266
as a governess.

01:56.266 --> 01:57.933
Today will be
my first day.

01:57.933 --> 02:00.366
Then I wish you every success.

02:00.366 --> 02:02.100
Though I'd venture you succeed
in whatever you put

02:02.100 --> 02:03.933
your mind to, Miss Heywood.

02:03.933 --> 02:05.633
Oh!

02:05.633 --> 02:08.233
And you can expect
an invitation.

02:08.233 --> 02:13.666
♪ ♪

02:13.666 --> 02:15.900
(bell tolling in distance)

02:15.900 --> 02:19.000
ARTHUR:
All the agent could tell us
is that Sidney was in Antigua

02:19.000 --> 02:20.466
on your behalf.

02:20.466 --> 02:21.600
GEORGIANA:
And yet he didn't think

02:21.600 --> 02:23.066
to tell me he was going?

02:23.066 --> 02:24.433
Or for what purpose?

02:24.433 --> 02:28.300
Well, he didn't tell
any of us.

02:28.300 --> 02:30.733
We have written
to your father's employees.

02:30.733 --> 02:35.133
But I'm afraid that it'll take
weeks to get a reply.

02:35.133 --> 02:38.900
I shall make my own
enquiries.

02:38.900 --> 02:40.600
What can this mean, Arthur?

02:40.600 --> 02:43.400
I am certain it's of
no cause for concern.

02:43.400 --> 02:46.466
Sidney will have had
your best interests at heart.

02:46.466 --> 02:48.600
Just as I do.

02:48.600 --> 02:50.066
(chuckles)

02:50.066 --> 02:54.900
♪ ♪

03:01.700 --> 03:03.666
(birds cawing)

03:05.533 --> 03:08.233
(bell ringing inside)

03:13.133 --> 03:16.133
♪ ♪

03:30.633 --> 03:32.033
LADY DENHAM:
No, no, no!

03:32.033 --> 03:34.900
I've never seen such a
fumble-fisted effort.

03:34.900 --> 03:37.700
You could always
do it yourself, Aunt.

03:37.700 --> 03:40.000
Well, then, what is the point
in having you here?

03:40.000 --> 03:41.700
Oh, leave them.
(knock at door)

03:41.700 --> 03:43.900
(door opens,
footsteps approaching)

03:43.900 --> 03:46.066
Give it
to Lady Babington.

03:50.833 --> 03:53.233
Well?
(door closes)

03:53.233 --> 03:55.766
Colonel Lennox has invited us
to a mess dinner.

03:55.766 --> 03:56.733
Oh.

03:56.733 --> 03:58.933
Oh, I'm not dining in a tent!

03:58.933 --> 04:00.800
Well, he's taken the
new Assembly Rooms.

04:00.800 --> 04:03.800
And you're thinking Edward
will be there.

04:03.800 --> 04:05.533
I can't help feeling,

04:05.533 --> 04:08.933
what with his reappearance and
Dr. Fuchs's prognosis,

04:08.933 --> 04:12.666
that God has taken
against me.

04:16.833 --> 04:22.000
♪ ♪

04:32.900 --> 04:35.366
MRS. WHEATLEY:
Miss Heywood,
you're late.

04:35.366 --> 04:38.033
We were expecting you
at 9:00.

04:38.033 --> 04:39.733
Mr. Colbourne has asked me
to tell you

04:39.733 --> 04:41.933
you will receive your monies
at the end of the month.

04:41.933 --> 04:46.133
Although few governesses
have lasted that long.

04:46.133 --> 04:47.266
The household is making wagers

04:47.266 --> 04:48.800
as to whether you'll last
the week.

04:48.800 --> 04:51.500
But I've a shilling says
you will, so for my sake...

04:51.500 --> 04:53.600
Be assured, Mrs. Wheatley,
your money is safe.

04:53.600 --> 04:56.566
Very little daunts me
when my mind is made up.

04:56.566 --> 04:59.100
When exactly did their
last governess...
COLBOURNE: Ah!

04:59.100 --> 05:01.333
Miss Heywood, they haven't
scared you away yet?

05:01.333 --> 05:03.233
Miss Heywood has only
just arrived, Mr. Colbourne.

05:03.233 --> 05:05.900
Then I shall introduce you
to your charges.

05:05.900 --> 05:07.033
Brace yourself.

05:07.033 --> 05:12.766
♪ ♪

05:15.600 --> 05:17.166
(Leonora exclaiming)

05:17.166 --> 05:18.400
Leonora?

05:26.833 --> 05:29.466
COLBOURNE:
Girls, you have met
Miss Heywood.

05:29.466 --> 05:31.033
She is to be
your new governess.

05:32.733 --> 05:33.900
Allow me
to reacquaint you.

05:33.900 --> 05:34.933
My daughter Leonora

05:34.933 --> 05:36.566
and my niece Augusta.

05:36.566 --> 05:38.300
Pleased to see you
both again.

05:38.300 --> 05:40.733
I trust you will show
Miss Heywood more courtesy

05:40.733 --> 05:43.000
than you afforded
her predecessor.

05:43.000 --> 05:45.600
Augusta, what was your
last lesson?

05:45.600 --> 05:47.233
Embroidery.

05:47.233 --> 05:49.400
Actually, I thought
perhaps we...
Your books will have to wait,

05:49.400 --> 05:51.633
Miss Heywood,
until you have taught them

05:51.633 --> 05:54.000
how to behave like
young ladies.

05:54.000 --> 05:56.333
Reading is hardly unladylike.

05:56.333 --> 06:00.033
As you can see, Leonora is in
dire need of a feminine hand,

06:00.033 --> 06:01.133
while Augusta

06:01.133 --> 06:03.800
lacks manners,
civility,

06:03.800 --> 06:04.900
or any of the qualities

06:04.900 --> 06:08.366
that would make her
remotely marriageable.

06:08.366 --> 06:09.366
Good luck.

06:09.366 --> 06:11.500
(door closes)

06:15.066 --> 06:17.500
You must learn to parry,
Miss Heywood,

06:17.500 --> 06:21.666
if you want to survive
this household.

06:21.666 --> 06:24.466
♪ ♪

06:24.466 --> 06:29.000
(seagulls cawing)

06:29.000 --> 06:31.766
(whispering indistinctly)

06:31.766 --> 06:37.033
♪ ♪

06:37.033 --> 06:39.900
She's a disgrace!

06:39.900 --> 06:41.433
(sighs)

06:41.433 --> 06:44.100
You must try and be a little
more restrained, my dear.

06:44.100 --> 06:46.866
It cost no small amount to
repair Lord Kingsley's carriage.

06:46.866 --> 06:47.966
And now Mr. Hartswood...

06:47.966 --> 06:50.400
Why are you so desperate
to see me married?

06:50.400 --> 06:52.433
(sighs)

06:52.433 --> 06:55.266
Society is not as kind
or as welcoming

06:55.266 --> 06:57.933
as one would hope, Georgiana.

06:57.933 --> 07:00.566
As you know only too well.

07:00.566 --> 07:03.333
And your fortune
leaves you vulnerable.

07:03.333 --> 07:05.666
A good marriage
will offer you protection.

07:05.666 --> 07:07.166
Acceptance.

07:07.166 --> 07:09.233
CHARLES:
Ladies.

07:09.233 --> 07:10.666
Mr. Lockhart.

07:10.666 --> 07:13.900
Why such a solemn demeanor
on this fine day, Miss Lambe?

07:13.900 --> 07:16.233
I was in a positively joyous
mood, Mr. Lockhart,

07:16.233 --> 07:17.566
until I saw you.

07:17.566 --> 07:18.800
Then I shall leave you to it,

07:18.800 --> 07:22.766
for fear of spoiling your mood
any further.

07:22.766 --> 07:27.166
♪ ♪

07:28.033 --> 07:30.100
ALISON:
He is approaching the house

07:30.100 --> 07:31.800
in his uniform!

07:31.800 --> 07:32.933
MARY:
Who?

07:32.933 --> 07:35.200
The soldier who saved me
from certain death!

07:35.200 --> 07:37.933
I do not even know his name.

07:37.933 --> 07:39.633
Oh, it is you?

07:39.633 --> 07:42.733
Oh, a pleasure to see you, too,
Miss Heywood.

07:42.733 --> 07:44.800
What is your business, sir?

07:44.800 --> 07:47.266
On behalf of Colonel Lennox,
I have the honor of inviting

07:47.266 --> 07:48.266
the Parker household

07:48.266 --> 07:50.066
to a mess dinner.

07:50.066 --> 07:51.100
And the colonel

07:51.100 --> 07:52.466
has expressly requested
the honor

07:52.466 --> 07:55.700
of Miss Charlotte Heywood's
company.

07:55.700 --> 07:57.700
I'm sure she will
graciously accept.

07:57.700 --> 07:58.633
Oh, and, uh,

07:58.633 --> 08:00.466
Captain Carter
sends his regards

08:00.466 --> 08:01.966
and regrets he is unable
to call in person.

08:01.966 --> 08:03.233
Captain Carter?

08:03.233 --> 08:04.900
Is he the soldier
from the beach?

08:04.900 --> 08:05.900
Young, handsome?

08:05.900 --> 08:07.533
He is young.

08:07.533 --> 08:10.500
And it's not for me
to say if he is handsome.

08:10.500 --> 08:13.133
Then send him my very best
regards in return.

08:13.133 --> 08:17.300
♪ ♪

08:18.800 --> 08:20.200
Carter!

08:20.200 --> 08:22.566
His name is Captain Carter!

08:22.566 --> 08:25.066
And this will be my first ever
grand dinner.

08:25.066 --> 08:27.766
I've already worn Charlotte's
good dress.

08:27.766 --> 08:29.400
I will gladly lend you
one of mine.

08:29.400 --> 08:30.466
You are a true friend!

08:30.466 --> 08:33.400
I wish it was Captain Carter
that had called.

08:33.400 --> 08:34.466
How am I to endure

08:34.466 --> 08:37.833
an entire day without seeing
his face?

08:37.833 --> 08:39.666
I saw a pretty hat this morning.

08:39.666 --> 08:41.966
Perhaps you'd like to come
and see it with me?

08:42.633 --> 08:45.533
Yes!

08:45.533 --> 08:48.700
CHARLOTTE:
If you gently pull the needle
up and through...

08:49.533 --> 08:51.233
AUGUSTA:
Miss Heywood.

08:51.233 --> 08:52.633
Yes, Miss Markham?

08:52.633 --> 08:54.666
It is Miss Heywood,
isn't it?

08:54.666 --> 08:55.766
Yes.

08:55.766 --> 08:57.766
Uh, then you are
not married?

08:57.766 --> 08:59.333
No.

08:59.333 --> 09:00.800
Nor have you ever been?

09:00.800 --> 09:01.933
No.

09:01.933 --> 09:05.166
Then how is that you are
to ready me for a life

09:05.166 --> 09:07.633
which you yourself
have quite roundly failed in?

09:07.633 --> 09:09.833
That is like having a

09:09.833 --> 09:12.633
riding instructor who has never
sat in a saddle.
(chuckles)

09:12.633 --> 09:13.866
LEONORA:
Or a pirate

09:13.866 --> 09:15.400
that's never gutted a man.

09:15.400 --> 09:16.500
Hmm.

09:16.500 --> 09:18.600
I have never been to France,

09:18.600 --> 09:20.133
yet my French is more
than passable.

09:20.133 --> 09:21.166
LEONORA:
Ouch!

09:21.166 --> 09:23.500
Damn these needles!

09:23.500 --> 09:25.366
Miss Colbourne.
AUGUSTA:
Do not give up.

09:25.366 --> 09:28.733
See what I have made
just for Miss Heywood.

09:28.733 --> 09:31.766
I do hope I have spelt
"spinster" right.

09:31.766 --> 09:33.166
You see it is not a word

09:33.166 --> 09:34.966
I am particularly
familiar with.

09:34.966 --> 09:36.666
Nor am I ever likely to be.

09:36.666 --> 09:37.733
(handbell ringing)

09:37.733 --> 09:39.333
I do believe it is time
for luncheon.

09:39.333 --> 09:41.000
Come along, Leo.

09:41.000 --> 09:42.933
The governess takes hers
in the kitchen, of course.

09:42.933 --> 09:45.200
Alone. But then again,

09:45.200 --> 09:50.300
I suppose you are used to that,
poor, dear Miss Heywood.

09:50.300 --> 09:54.566
(footsteps retreating,
Augusta and Leonora giggling)

09:54.566 --> 09:59.700
♪ ♪

10:18.466 --> 10:21.900
EDWARD:
Esther.

10:21.900 --> 10:23.500
Forgive me, I didn't expect
to find you here.

10:23.500 --> 10:26.900
On the promenade
or in Sanditon?

10:26.900 --> 10:28.233
Either, if I'm honest.

10:28.233 --> 10:30.666
And yet does it not feel like
fate that we should both

10:30.666 --> 10:32.566
find ourselves back here
at the same time?

10:32.566 --> 10:34.700
Fate played no part in this.

10:34.700 --> 10:35.800
It's all a contrivance.

10:35.800 --> 10:38.466
You're fooling no one,
least of all me.

10:41.266 --> 10:43.966
What will it take to convince
you I'm truly repentant?

10:43.966 --> 10:45.333
Try drowning yourself.

10:45.333 --> 10:48.133
♪ ♪

10:48.133 --> 10:50.600
MRS. WHEATLEY:
Miss Markham's work,
I assume?

10:50.600 --> 10:52.666
She is very... adept.

10:52.666 --> 10:54.466
On the contrary.

10:54.466 --> 10:56.333
I see several
dropped stitches.

10:56.333 --> 10:58.666
You're not going to let her
get away with that?

10:58.666 --> 11:00.233
I don't want to
punish her, Mrs. Wheatley.

11:00.233 --> 11:02.433
I want to understand her.

11:02.433 --> 11:04.166
Is it so hard
to understand?

11:04.166 --> 11:06.033
She's 18 years old
and not long orphaned.

11:06.033 --> 11:09.700
And Leonora lost her mother,
too?

11:09.700 --> 11:11.066
That was many years ago now.

11:11.066 --> 11:12.533
We don't dwell on it.

11:12.533 --> 11:14.400
Remember, girl,
I've a shilling on you.

11:19.766 --> 11:20.766
HANKINS:
Lady Babington!

11:20.766 --> 11:23.133
(chuckling):
You appear to be

11:23.133 --> 11:24.766
our sole congregant for matins!

11:24.766 --> 11:25.933
(chuckles)

11:25.933 --> 11:29.666
Oh, you will remember,
of course, my dear sister,

11:29.666 --> 11:31.033
Miss Beatrice Hankins?

11:31.033 --> 11:32.600
A pleasure,
Lady Babington.

11:32.600 --> 11:34.300
I cannot stay,

11:34.300 --> 11:35.300
thrilling as matins sounds.

11:35.300 --> 11:38.166
And, uh, how is married life?

11:38.166 --> 11:39.933
Will, uh, Lord Babington
be joining us

11:39.933 --> 11:40.933
during the summer months?

11:40.933 --> 11:42.600
I do hope so.

11:42.600 --> 11:46.433
It is not right for husband
and wife to be too long apart.

11:46.433 --> 11:49.100
Not if they wish to bless
their home with children.

11:49.100 --> 11:51.566
As the Psalms tell us,
"Children are an heritage

11:51.566 --> 11:52.633
of the Lord."

11:52.633 --> 11:54.433
"And the fruit of the womb
is his reward."

11:54.433 --> 11:56.200
That is no concern of yours!

12:00.933 --> 12:03.366
I forgot to mention
the charity darning circle.

12:03.366 --> 12:05.166
Oh...

12:05.166 --> 12:06.733
(bird cawing)

12:06.733 --> 12:09.433
Lady Babington?

12:09.433 --> 12:10.933
Lady Babington.

12:12.033 --> 12:13.266
We are not well acquainted,

12:13.266 --> 12:15.266
and I do not wish to presume...
You already have,

12:15.266 --> 12:17.966
Miss Hankins.
Oh, forgive me.

12:17.966 --> 12:19.600
But I am a Christian woman,
with Christian feeling,

12:19.600 --> 12:22.300
and recognize when another
of my sex is in need.

12:22.300 --> 12:23.266
Thank you.

12:23.266 --> 12:25.733
I am in no need
of your charity.

12:25.733 --> 12:28.600
It is not charity
I am offering.

12:28.600 --> 12:31.933
(quietly):
I have heard tell
of a midwife of Melmead.

12:31.933 --> 12:34.033
A Mrs. Potter.

12:34.033 --> 12:36.466
She helps women who have

12:36.466 --> 12:39.966
struggled, as I believe
you might be

12:39.966 --> 12:42.600
struggling.

12:42.600 --> 12:44.200
Well...

12:44.200 --> 12:46.433
I have done my part.

12:46.433 --> 12:49.533
The rest is in God's hands.

12:49.533 --> 12:54.733
♪ ♪

12:54.733 --> 12:57.266
ARTHUR:
This is just a crude rendering,
of course,

12:57.266 --> 13:00.366
but it gives you
a sense of it.

13:00.366 --> 13:03.100
And it would sit right here.

13:03.100 --> 13:09.033
The Theatre Royal Sanditon!

13:09.033 --> 13:11.666
It, it is a wonderful idea,
brother.

13:11.666 --> 13:13.200
Hm? Oh...

13:13.200 --> 13:14.566
But this would
require

13:14.566 --> 13:17.533
a great deal of investment
and we cannot afford to gamble.

13:17.533 --> 13:19.400
Speculators speculate!

13:19.400 --> 13:20.900
That's what you have always
said.

13:20.900 --> 13:22.800
Yes, that does sound like me.

13:22.800 --> 13:24.300
We shall talk
more of it anon.

13:24.300 --> 13:26.366
But now I have promised
to give Colonel Lennox

13:26.366 --> 13:28.866
a tour of Sanditon.

13:32.300 --> 13:36.233
Come on, Arthur!

13:36.233 --> 13:39.066
We are most honored
by the invitation, Colonel.

13:39.066 --> 13:41.266
I cannot tell you
the excitement it has caused

13:41.266 --> 13:44.100
amongst the women
of our household.

13:44.100 --> 13:45.866
(chuckles):
We have been made
so welcome by the town.

13:45.866 --> 13:47.466
I hope the dinner
will go some small way

13:47.466 --> 13:48.500
towards showing our gratitude.

13:48.500 --> 13:49.800
(chuckling):
Yes.

13:49.800 --> 13:52.500
Now, if you look up there,
Colonel, you will see

13:52.500 --> 13:57.266
we are just finishing
the Seaview Apartments,

13:57.266 --> 14:00.000
and now we are considering

14:00.000 --> 14:01.500
our next expansion.

14:01.500 --> 14:03.800
We have been discussing
a theater.

14:03.800 --> 14:06.366
I've been drawing up
grand plans:

14:06.366 --> 14:07.900
a gilt proscenium,
a balcony...

14:07.900 --> 14:08.900
Well, well, yes,

14:08.900 --> 14:11.266
at some future point, Arthur,
perhaps.

14:11.266 --> 14:13.566
But right now,
we cannot afford

14:13.566 --> 14:16.733
to take any risks if we are to
repay Sidney's investment.

14:16.733 --> 14:17.766
Sidney?

14:17.766 --> 14:19.366
Our dear departed brother.

14:19.366 --> 14:21.566
It was he that secured
Sanditon's future.

14:21.566 --> 14:24.200
What a fine legacy,
Mr. Parker.

14:24.200 --> 14:25.566
Thank you, sir.

14:25.566 --> 14:26.966
Were Sidney here,
I am sure that you and he

14:26.966 --> 14:27.966
would find much in common.

14:27.966 --> 14:29.133
ARTHUR:
Some things.

14:29.133 --> 14:31.166
(chuckling):
Perhaps.

14:31.166 --> 14:32.366
TOM:
And he would want to
encourage you,

14:32.366 --> 14:33.533
as I do,

14:33.533 --> 14:35.533
to consider extending
your stay indefinitely.

14:35.533 --> 14:37.433
I've been thinking further
on the idea

14:37.433 --> 14:39.533
of a permanent barracks.

14:39.533 --> 14:42.300
Which I feel could be
of great mutual benefit.

14:42.300 --> 14:43.333
With your permission, Colonel,

14:43.333 --> 14:45.300
I have a site
I wish to show you.

14:45.300 --> 14:47.400
By all means, Tom.

14:47.400 --> 14:48.833
(chuckles)

14:49.966 --> 14:53.700
Theatre Royal Sanditon.

14:53.700 --> 14:56.766
♪ ♪

14:56.766 --> 14:58.700
ALISON:
Are you sure this is wise,
Miss Lambe?

14:58.700 --> 14:59.633
Or appropriate?

14:59.633 --> 15:02.366
I have had my fill
of being told

15:02.366 --> 15:05.800
what is and isn't
appropriate.

15:05.800 --> 15:08.200
FRASER:
Left, right...

15:08.200 --> 15:10.066
Do not betray your feelings
too readily.

15:10.066 --> 15:11.833
Try to appear aloof.

15:11.833 --> 15:13.066
We've invaded his camp.

15:13.066 --> 15:16.000
It is hardly aloof.

15:16.000 --> 15:17.166
FRASER:
Come on.

15:19.200 --> 15:20.733
Ready?

15:20.733 --> 15:22.000
Right!

15:22.000 --> 15:23.600
Left!

15:23.600 --> 15:25.433
Head! Right! Left!

15:25.433 --> 15:27.566
Head!

15:27.566 --> 15:28.933
Right! Up!

15:28.933 --> 15:30.833
Right! Left!

15:30.833 --> 15:32.700
Left! Right!

15:35.300 --> 15:37.800
(Carter groans, Alison gasps)

15:37.800 --> 15:39.633
Miss Heywood?

15:39.633 --> 15:42.800
Ladies, this is no place
for a young woman.

15:42.800 --> 15:44.533
Let them stay a moment,
Fraser.

15:44.533 --> 15:45.966
I am unharmed.

15:45.966 --> 15:47.233
I simply came to thank you, sir,

15:47.233 --> 15:49.233
for saving me so gallantly
yesterday.

15:49.233 --> 15:51.833
I cannot take all the credit,
miss.

15:51.833 --> 15:54.066
You have my undying gratitude.

15:55.166 --> 15:58.266
Miss Heywood, you are to attend
the mess dinner?

15:58.266 --> 16:00.033
I would not miss it
for the world.

16:00.033 --> 16:01.933
Then I might be so bold
as to request the first dance

16:01.933 --> 16:02.900
of the evening.

16:02.900 --> 16:04.266
I would be honored to.

16:04.266 --> 16:05.266
FRASER:
I must insist you ladies

16:05.266 --> 16:06.333
leave the camp.

16:06.333 --> 16:08.400
I shall escort you
to the bridge.

16:08.400 --> 16:10.900
Really, sir,
have you no heart at all?

16:10.900 --> 16:12.433
None.

16:12.433 --> 16:14.466
Just a cold, hard rock
in its place.

16:14.466 --> 16:18.466
♪ ♪

16:18.466 --> 16:22.100
(birds twittering)

16:22.100 --> 16:23.533
LEONORA:
Look, there's another one!

16:23.533 --> 16:25.533
CHARLOTTE (gasps):
Well done, Miss Colbourne.

16:28.766 --> 16:32.433
And what do we do with
our specimens, Miss Heywood?

16:32.433 --> 16:35.133
We shall examine them,
like malacologists.

16:39.033 --> 16:40.400
This silly dress!

16:40.400 --> 16:42.666
I wish I could wear
my short britches.

16:42.666 --> 16:44.633
They would be rather more
practical.

16:44.633 --> 16:46.800
Father says
it's unladylike.

16:46.800 --> 16:49.066
My mother says a woman
should dress appropriately

16:49.066 --> 16:51.700
for whatever activity
she is engaged upon.

16:51.700 --> 16:54.700
I'm not sure my father
would agree with that.

16:58.200 --> 17:01.333
Is she still alive,
your mother?

17:02.500 --> 17:05.433
Yes, she is.

17:05.433 --> 17:09.133
I don't miss mine,
before you ask.

17:09.133 --> 17:12.033
Although Father doesn't even
like us to mention her name.

17:13.400 --> 17:15.233
What do you remember of her?
Nothing.

17:15.233 --> 17:17.666
She died when I was a baby.

17:18.600 --> 17:20.300
You must miss her a little.

17:20.300 --> 17:23.000
You can't miss
what you never had.

17:23.000 --> 17:25.233
Of course you can.

17:25.233 --> 17:29.733
For example, Miss Heywood misses
the husband she doesn't have.

17:29.733 --> 17:30.766
Don't you?

17:30.766 --> 17:33.966
♪ ♪

17:33.966 --> 17:37.300
(waves lapping,
seagulls cawing)

17:37.300 --> 17:39.000
(yawns)

17:39.000 --> 17:40.700
Do not move!

17:40.700 --> 17:41.700
Please!

17:41.700 --> 17:42.900
I only have
a silk handkerchief.

17:42.900 --> 17:45.133
(laughs)

17:45.133 --> 17:47.200
Fear not, Mr. Parker.

17:47.200 --> 17:49.566
I could not resist such a
peaceful subject.

17:50.666 --> 17:53.300
Then I am honored, sir.

17:53.300 --> 17:55.333
Honored.

17:55.333 --> 17:57.700
Might I be permitted to...
Oh!

18:00.133 --> 18:02.433
You have a rare talent.

18:02.433 --> 18:04.400
Please.

18:06.700 --> 18:10.300
I should very much like
to paint your friend Miss Lambe.

18:11.600 --> 18:13.266
But I fear she's taken
against me.

18:13.266 --> 18:15.300
Oh, that is just her manner.
(chuckles)

18:15.300 --> 18:16.866
She clearly holds you
in high esteem.

18:16.866 --> 18:19.033
Perhaps you could convince her

18:19.033 --> 18:20.600
that I am not entirely
without merit.

18:20.600 --> 18:22.633
I would forever be in your debt.

18:22.633 --> 18:23.700
Oh, say no more, sir.

18:23.700 --> 18:25.933
I shall make it my mission.

18:25.933 --> 18:27.833
In the meantime,
you shall have to

18:27.833 --> 18:31.933
content yourself with
a much less beguiling model.

18:31.933 --> 18:33.100
I will not hear it.

18:33.100 --> 18:37.600
You have a rare masculine
beauty, Mr. Parker.

18:37.600 --> 18:40.266
Indeed?
Undoubtedly so.

18:40.266 --> 18:43.300
In Paris, you would be fêted
in the salons for your charm

18:43.300 --> 18:46.566
and in the Tuileries
for your style.

18:46.566 --> 18:49.800
(chuckling):
Oh, I should love to be
fêted in the Tuileries!

18:49.800 --> 18:51.966
(laughs)

18:51.966 --> 18:54.533
And I am certain one day,
you shall.

18:54.533 --> 18:56.266
(chuckles)

18:56.266 --> 19:03.700
♪ ♪

19:06.800 --> 19:08.733
Can we really make a home
for the water snails?

19:08.733 --> 19:09.900
Of course.

19:09.900 --> 19:12.000
Now, if we could find
a magnifying glass...

19:12.000 --> 19:14.400
I suspect there is one
in your father's study.

19:14.400 --> 19:15.800
Oh! Miss Colbourne!

19:19.166 --> 19:20.933
Leonora,
it is customary to knock.

19:20.933 --> 19:21.900
What is so urgent?

19:21.900 --> 19:23.700
Look!

19:23.700 --> 19:25.433
Snails?

19:26.566 --> 19:28.066
CHARLOTTE:
Water snails, sir.

19:28.066 --> 19:31.233
We collected them from the pond
to examine them more closely.

19:31.233 --> 19:33.933
We were in want
of a magnifying glass.

19:33.933 --> 19:36.833
COLBOURNE:
Really, well, one snail...

19:37.700 --> 19:39.333
One magnifying glass.

19:39.333 --> 19:41.233
Which I shall need back.

19:41.233 --> 19:42.833
Thank you.

19:42.833 --> 19:44.633
We're being malacologists.

19:44.633 --> 19:46.233
Would you like to see
our other specimens?

19:46.233 --> 19:47.233
Tempting as that is,

19:47.233 --> 19:49.966
I shall have to decline.

19:49.966 --> 19:53.333
CHARLOTTE:
Come, Miss Colbourne,
your father is busy.

19:55.600 --> 19:57.200
Miss Heywood.

19:57.200 --> 19:59.066
Forgive me,
I must have been unclear.

19:59.066 --> 20:02.633
I thought I engaged you to make
a young lady of Leonora.

20:02.633 --> 20:04.900
That is precisely
what I'm doing.

20:04.900 --> 20:06.733
By trawling ponds for mollusks?

20:06.733 --> 20:07.833
I am widening her knowledge.

20:07.833 --> 20:10.333
She has no interest
in embroidery, sir.

20:10.333 --> 20:11.700
And you see how engaged she is.

20:11.700 --> 20:13.733
If you could just spare a moment
to let her show you...

20:13.733 --> 20:15.133
Thank you,
Miss Heywood,

20:15.133 --> 20:17.500
but you are here to further
the girls' education, not mine.

20:18.633 --> 20:20.233
Then I shall leave you
to your work, sir.

20:20.233 --> 20:22.366
Planorbis carinatus.

20:22.366 --> 20:24.033
Keeled ram's horn.

20:24.033 --> 20:25.400
If you're going to be
malacologists,

20:25.400 --> 20:27.866
you might as well use
the correct terminology.

20:30.533 --> 20:33.900
♪ ♪

20:51.666 --> 20:53.800
Thank you.

20:53.800 --> 20:55.900
(giggling)

20:55.900 --> 20:58.666
You don't look quite as excited
as your sister.

20:58.666 --> 20:59.933
But then, who does?

20:59.933 --> 21:02.900
I confess I am strangely
apprehensive.

21:02.900 --> 21:05.033
The last time I danced
in Sanditon...

21:05.033 --> 21:06.366
Was with Sidney.

21:06.366 --> 21:09.033
You must try to put that
from your mind.

21:10.066 --> 21:11.433
We're going to enjoy
ourselves tonight.

21:11.433 --> 21:14.766
We shall eat and drink and dance
and forget all our cares!

21:14.766 --> 21:15.900
I insist upon it.

21:17.500 --> 21:19.300
Ladies, it's my honor
to welcome you this evening.

21:19.300 --> 21:20.533
Miss Heywood,

21:20.533 --> 21:22.300
it's a particular pleasure
to see you again.

21:22.300 --> 21:24.266
After supper, might I claim
the first dance?

21:24.266 --> 21:25.666
Thank you, sir.

21:25.666 --> 21:29.933
Excuse me, Colonel, but I really
must greet the family Parker.

21:29.933 --> 21:30.933
So, Miss Heywood,

21:30.933 --> 21:33.500
how are you finding
your new job?

21:33.500 --> 21:35.333
Thus far, highly rewarding.

21:36.833 --> 21:37.933
You doubt me, sir.

21:37.933 --> 21:40.400
You've previously spoken
with such candor.

21:40.400 --> 21:41.600
It is strange to hear you
dissemble.

21:41.600 --> 21:43.733
(sighing, quietly):
I have two charges.

21:43.733 --> 21:44.866
One I've gained
some ground with,

21:44.866 --> 21:47.500
but the elder girl is...
resistant.

21:47.500 --> 21:51.333
(quietly):
Gaining ground is my vocation,
Miss Heywood.

21:51.333 --> 21:53.933
We shall form a battle strategy
before the night is out.

21:53.933 --> 21:55.233
(chuckles)

21:55.233 --> 21:56.833
LADY DENHAM:
Herbs?!

21:56.833 --> 22:00.700
I should never have thought
you so credulous!

22:00.700 --> 22:05.233
Neither Fuchs nor any doctor
I have consulted can help me.

22:05.233 --> 22:08.433
Fuchs sounds positively rational
besides this charlatan.

22:08.433 --> 22:10.066
And you went to her house?

22:10.066 --> 22:11.066
She is no charlatan.

22:11.066 --> 22:12.033
Mrs. Potter has assisted

22:12.033 --> 22:13.133
many women.

22:13.133 --> 22:15.966
And if nothing else,
she has given me hope.

22:15.966 --> 22:17.833
What do I have to lose?

22:19.933 --> 22:22.233
(sighing):
I knew we should not
have come.

22:22.233 --> 22:23.666
LADY DENHAM:
Pay him no heed.

22:23.666 --> 22:24.700
He is no threat

22:24.700 --> 22:26.733
to either of us.

22:26.733 --> 22:31.066
♪ ♪

22:31.066 --> 22:32.766
LADY DENHAM:
Miss Heywood, Miss Lambe.

22:33.566 --> 22:34.666
GEORGIANA:
Lady Denham.

22:34.666 --> 22:36.666
Lady Babington.

22:36.666 --> 22:39.600
I understand you are behind this
sugar boycott, Miss Lambe.

22:39.600 --> 22:41.833
I take it you won't be
joining us.

22:41.833 --> 22:45.800
Life affords few enough
pleasures as it is.

22:45.800 --> 22:47.133
Forgive me, my lady.

22:47.133 --> 22:49.900
I'd forgotten you lived a life
of such deprivation.

22:49.900 --> 22:53.400
Alison,
I spy Captain Carter.

22:53.400 --> 22:56.533
♪ ♪

22:56.533 --> 22:58.666
Oh, oh, Miss Lambe,
Miss Heywood.

22:58.666 --> 23:02.733
I, I believe you have met
my dear friend Mr. Lockhart.

23:02.733 --> 23:04.166
I wasn't aware you were
so well acquainted.

23:04.166 --> 23:05.233
Oh, yes!

23:05.233 --> 23:07.566
I, I cannot praise
this gentleman enough.

23:07.566 --> 23:11.833
He is a fine fellow,
and, and, I might add,

23:11.833 --> 23:13.866
quite a remarkable
portraitist.

23:13.866 --> 23:15.000
I shall take your word for it.

23:15.000 --> 23:16.066
CHARLES:
Are you not inclined

23:16.066 --> 23:18.133
to make your own opinion,
Miss Lambe?

23:18.133 --> 23:20.066
I already have.

23:20.066 --> 23:21.400
Excuse us.

23:21.400 --> 23:23.766
♪ ♪

23:23.766 --> 23:27.000
She is definitely
warming up to you.

23:27.000 --> 23:30.166
(chuckles):
I admire your optimism.

23:31.800 --> 23:36.466
Excuse me one moment,
Mr. Lockhart.

23:36.466 --> 23:42.466
♪ ♪

23:43.000 --> 23:45.033
Oh, excusez-moi.

23:45.033 --> 23:46.200
Ah.

23:48.066 --> 23:49.533
Huh.

23:49.533 --> 23:53.166
♪ ♪

23:57.166 --> 24:00.400
Remember,
try not to seem too eager.

24:08.033 --> 24:11.233
♪ ♪

24:11.233 --> 24:12.800
Miss Heywood.

24:12.800 --> 24:14.433
Captain Carter.

24:14.433 --> 24:16.233
How elegant you look.

24:16.233 --> 24:17.466
Thank you.

24:17.466 --> 24:19.166
And what a beautiful setting.

24:19.166 --> 24:21.266
I am reminded of
these lines of Cowper:

24:21.266 --> 24:23.566
"I fly to scenes romantic."

24:23.566 --> 24:25.166
I feel as though
I have flown here myself.

24:25.166 --> 24:26.133
Indeed.

24:26.133 --> 24:27.833
Cowper, yes.

24:27.833 --> 24:29.833
What a genius he is.

24:29.833 --> 24:31.600
I worship his poetry.

24:31.600 --> 24:32.900
As do I!

24:32.900 --> 24:34.233
Which is your favorite?

24:34.233 --> 24:37.400
I, uh...
(chuckles)

24:37.400 --> 24:39.700
I could hardly choose!
(laughs)

24:46.333 --> 24:50.166
Supper, Miss Lambe!

24:50.166 --> 24:53.400
♪ ♪

24:55.800 --> 24:58.466
What a fine table, Colonel.

24:58.466 --> 24:59.633
Thank you, milady.

24:59.633 --> 25:01.566
I'm glad it meets your approval.

25:01.566 --> 25:06.933
♪ ♪

25:06.933 --> 25:10.366
Where are you, Charlotte?

25:10.366 --> 25:11.433
BEATRICE:
Miss Heywood!

25:11.433 --> 25:14.000
You're down here, with us.

25:14.000 --> 25:15.066
Oh...

25:15.066 --> 25:16.800
This is what comes
of being a governess.

25:16.800 --> 25:18.066
Forced to sit with the
spinsters.

25:18.066 --> 25:19.766
Cast out from society.
Hardly.

25:19.766 --> 25:22.533
(quietly):
It's only the other end
of the table.

25:22.533 --> 25:28.500
♪ ♪

25:28.500 --> 25:30.100
Miss Heywood.

25:30.100 --> 25:32.800
It seems we are to be
seated together.

25:32.800 --> 25:34.200
I hope you can endure
my company

25:34.200 --> 25:36.433
since you are so often keen
to be rid of me.

25:36.433 --> 25:40.666
I shall have to endure it
as stoically as I can.

25:40.666 --> 25:43.633
♪ ♪

25:52.500 --> 25:55.900
♪ ♪

25:55.900 --> 25:57.066
ARTHUR:
Good gracious!

25:57.066 --> 25:59.133
(chuckles)

25:59.133 --> 26:00.300
What luck!

26:00.300 --> 26:04.933
♪ ♪

26:04.933 --> 26:09.866
(drums pounding)

26:15.333 --> 26:21.233
(applauding)

26:21.233 --> 26:26.400
♪ ♪

26:39.166 --> 26:41.533
ARTHUR:
Is not this repast

26:41.533 --> 26:44.100
delicious, Mr. Lockhart?

26:44.100 --> 26:46.466
I thought the lamb
was a little tough.

26:46.466 --> 26:48.433
And somewhat cold.

26:48.433 --> 26:51.366
If it is so unpalatable,
why don't you leave it?

26:51.366 --> 26:54.200
I am sure it
would not miss you.

26:54.200 --> 26:57.100
I'm waiting for it
to surprise me.

26:57.100 --> 27:00.233
Why should it?

27:00.233 --> 27:02.066
Well, I think it's jolly well
delightful.

27:02.066 --> 27:03.733
(chuckles)

27:05.133 --> 27:06.933
FRASER:
Shall I ask

27:06.933 --> 27:09.400
Captain Carter
if we might exchange places?

27:09.400 --> 27:11.333
Forgive me,
I do not mean to be rude.

27:11.333 --> 27:12.566
I'm not in the least
offended.

27:12.566 --> 27:16.666
I cannot blame you for seeking
his company over mine.

27:16.666 --> 27:20.766
He is unforgivably handsome,
after all.

27:20.766 --> 27:23.266
Are you mocking me?

27:23.266 --> 27:25.566
I wouldn't dream of it.

27:29.500 --> 27:31.233
Yes, I, uh...
(clears throat)

27:31.233 --> 27:32.800
I considered the Army myself.

27:32.800 --> 27:35.700
But ultimately, uh,
I felt that

27:35.700 --> 27:38.933
my gift for oratory was
better suited to the church.

27:38.933 --> 27:41.066
(chuckles)

27:41.066 --> 27:44.333
Besides, one of my legs
is a full inch shorter

27:44.333 --> 27:46.833
than the other,
which might have proved

27:46.833 --> 27:49.700
disadvantageous in battle.

27:49.700 --> 27:54.233
But now you serve
the King of all kings, brother!

27:54.233 --> 27:55.600
Yes.

27:55.600 --> 28:00.700
(people talking in background)

28:00.700 --> 28:03.233
(quietly):
I notice the other ladies
are enthralled

28:03.233 --> 28:06.166
by the soldiers in our midst,
yet you seem quite indifferent.

28:06.166 --> 28:07.700
It takes a good deal
more than a red coat

28:07.700 --> 28:10.266
and some brass buttons
to impress me.

28:10.266 --> 28:11.400
Likewise.

28:11.400 --> 28:14.200
I find our island's veneration
for the military

28:14.200 --> 28:15.966
vaguely repulsive.

28:15.966 --> 28:17.966
And yet you accepted
the colonel's invitation.

28:17.966 --> 28:21.466
Is that not
rather hypocritical?

28:22.766 --> 28:27.100
I accepted out of curiosity
and boredom.

28:27.100 --> 28:28.366
What's your excuse?

28:28.366 --> 28:30.466
I had little choice.

28:30.466 --> 28:32.800
It would have been considered

28:32.800 --> 28:34.500
very ill-mannered of me
to decline.

28:34.500 --> 28:37.033
You didn't strike me
as someone overly concerned

28:37.033 --> 28:40.433
with winning the approval
of others.

28:40.433 --> 28:42.400
I must admit

28:42.400 --> 28:44.633
I'm quite disappointed.

28:44.633 --> 28:48.066
Then it is a good thing your
opinion means nothing to me.

28:49.900 --> 28:50.966
LENNOX:
Gentlemen.

28:50.966 --> 28:52.533
(chairs shifting)

28:52.533 --> 28:53.566
The king.

28:53.566 --> 28:55.533
MEN:
The king!

28:59.233 --> 29:05.366
♪ ♪

29:05.366 --> 29:06.633
CHARLES:
I should like to make

29:06.633 --> 29:08.333
a toast of my own.

29:08.333 --> 29:12.066
♪ ♪

29:12.066 --> 29:13.333
In 1814,

29:13.333 --> 29:16.100
Emperor Napoleon
abolished slavery.

29:16.100 --> 29:17.833
He was not just a soldier,

29:17.833 --> 29:21.833
but a man of vision.

29:21.833 --> 29:24.133
A man who recognized

29:24.133 --> 29:26.833
that ideas...

29:28.033 --> 29:30.033
....rule the world.

29:30.033 --> 29:33.033
Not might alone.

29:33.033 --> 29:35.400
(chuckles)

29:35.400 --> 29:39.033
To Napoleon Bonaparte.

29:39.033 --> 29:40.333
(soldiers pounding table)

29:40.333 --> 29:45.700
SOLDIERS (chanting):
Out! Out! Out! Out!

29:45.700 --> 29:47.033
Thank you.

29:47.033 --> 29:52.466
(pounding and chanting continue)

29:52.466 --> 29:53.766
(pounding and chanting stop)

29:53.766 --> 29:54.766
LADY DENHAM:
Ignore him.

29:54.766 --> 29:56.866
He's just an artist.

29:56.866 --> 30:00.600
♪ ♪

30:08.433 --> 30:13.633
(people talking softly,
instruments tuning)

30:15.833 --> 30:17.500
I am sorry we could not
be seated together.

30:17.500 --> 30:20.633
You might have saved me from my
infuriating dinner companion.

30:20.633 --> 30:22.600
He certainly caused
quite a scandal.

30:22.600 --> 30:23.933
Did I notice you smile?

30:23.933 --> 30:25.733
Certainly not!

30:25.733 --> 30:27.133
It was a grimace.

30:27.133 --> 30:29.100
Although I have a feeling
you'll shortly have cause

30:29.100 --> 30:31.033
to smile yourself.
LENNOX:
Miss Heywood.

30:31.033 --> 30:32.933
CHARLOTTE:
Colonel Lennox.

30:32.933 --> 30:37.400
(people talking in background)

30:37.400 --> 30:39.066
ARTHUR:
Miss Lambe,

30:39.066 --> 30:40.400
you should be dancing.

30:40.400 --> 30:41.500
I insist upon it.

30:41.500 --> 30:44.033
I have been waiting for you.

30:44.033 --> 30:45.866
(both giggling)

30:45.866 --> 30:52.066
(people talking in background)

30:52.066 --> 30:55.433
Miss Heywood, would you still
do me the honor?

30:55.433 --> 30:57.466
With the greatest
of pleasure, sir.

30:57.466 --> 31:02.800
(music playing)

31:18.300 --> 31:21.600
Given you profess to
loathe the man,

31:21.600 --> 31:25.066
you do seem rather
fascinated by him.

31:25.066 --> 31:27.033
As do you, Arthur.

31:27.033 --> 31:29.533
&nbsp;
(Arthur chuckles)

31:29.533 --> 31:34.733
(music continues)

31:34.733 --> 31:37.800
I must apologize for the
seating arrangements at dinner.

31:37.800 --> 31:39.266
If it weren't for convention,
I would have...

31:39.266 --> 31:40.333
It's all right.

31:40.333 --> 31:42.666
I know my place
as a lowly governess.

31:42.666 --> 31:45.900
There's nothing lowly about you,
Miss Heywood.

31:47.800 --> 31:53.433
(music continues)

32:04.500 --> 32:09.400
(music continues)

32:17.500 --> 32:23.733
(music continues)

32:31.700 --> 32:36.300
Do you remember the first time
we danced together?

32:36.300 --> 32:41.066
The day my father
married your mother.

32:41.066 --> 32:45.033
It took me an hour to find
the courage to ask you.

32:45.033 --> 32:48.166
I was in awe of you then.

32:50.400 --> 32:53.466
I still am.

32:53.466 --> 32:57.333
♪ ♪

33:01.033 --> 33:06.266
(Schubert's Marche Militaire
No. 1 playing)

33:21.233 --> 33:24.700
That one doesn't let
the grass grow.

33:24.700 --> 33:28.200
In battle, we defeated our enemy
by holding fire

33:28.200 --> 33:29.566
until he was very close,

33:29.566 --> 33:33.066
then charging with bayonets
and firing a single volley.

33:33.066 --> 33:35.500
A rather extreme strategy for
educating an 18-year-old girl,

33:35.500 --> 33:38.566
wouldn't you say?

33:38.566 --> 33:42.466
My meaning is,
wait till your enemy's close,

33:42.466 --> 33:44.466
then you may take
your best shot.

33:44.466 --> 33:47.800
Let her see you,
you may best see her.

33:51.833 --> 33:52.833
(piece ends)

33:52.833 --> 33:55.500
(applauding)

33:55.500 --> 33:57.333
Perhaps that's true.

33:57.333 --> 33:58.900
I should be more open with her.

33:58.900 --> 34:01.533
Then hopefully I shall have
no need to employ the bayonet.

34:01.533 --> 34:04.900
(chuckles)

34:04.900 --> 34:06.633
(people talking in background)

34:06.633 --> 34:07.866
TOM:
Colonel.

34:07.866 --> 34:09.233
ARTHUR:
Oh, excuse me.

34:09.233 --> 34:10.233
Arthur.

34:10.233 --> 34:13.666
Yes, brother, I'm here.

34:13.666 --> 34:17.033
At supper, Colonel Lennox
was highly complimentary

34:17.033 --> 34:18.866
about your stepbrother.

34:18.866 --> 34:22.266
I didn't recognize
the man he described.

34:24.000 --> 34:27.033
Apologies for the Lockhart
fellow's outburst.

34:27.033 --> 34:29.833
Believe me, he does not
represent Sanditon.

34:29.833 --> 34:32.166
ARTHUR:
It's just his sense of humor.

34:32.166 --> 34:33.266
Please, gentlemen.

34:33.266 --> 34:35.200
(men cheering,
laughing raucously)

34:35.200 --> 34:37.066
So...
To friendship.

34:37.066 --> 34:38.066
To friendship.

34:38.066 --> 34:40.266
♪ ♪

34:40.266 --> 34:42.500
Now, let's forget any troubles
we have with a game.

34:42.500 --> 34:44.766
This is not the time
to gamble.

34:44.766 --> 34:46.166
My brother is right.

34:46.166 --> 34:47.966
I do not wish
to lose my money.

34:47.966 --> 34:49.000
Then I'll stake you.

34:49.000 --> 34:50.133
(men cheering)

34:50.133 --> 34:51.600
Captain Carter, the dice.

34:51.600 --> 34:53.566
I'm staking Mr. Parker
five pounds.

34:53.566 --> 34:55.433
Tom?

34:56.066 --> 34:57.766
&nbsp;
Well, Tom?

34:59.133 --> 35:01.366
Are you in or out?

35:05.366 --> 35:09.733
♪ ♪

35:09.733 --> 35:11.633
Knock.

35:11.633 --> 35:13.366
(knocks)

35:13.366 --> 35:14.833
Now you throw for main point.

35:14.833 --> 35:17.333
Which means you need the five,
six, seven, eight, or nine.

35:17.333 --> 35:19.633
Of course--
main point.

35:19.633 --> 35:22.033
(dice rattling)

35:22.033 --> 35:23.866
(dice clatter)

35:23.866 --> 35:24.900
CARTER:
Seven!

35:24.900 --> 35:26.666
Hey!

35:26.666 --> 35:28.066
Very good.

35:28.066 --> 35:31.400
♪ ♪

35:31.400 --> 35:36.966
(music playing)

35:41.800 --> 35:43.933
I suppose that toast
was for my benefit.

35:45.333 --> 35:47.300
Don't flatter yourself.

35:49.066 --> 35:50.533
It was for my own amusement.

35:50.533 --> 35:52.000
And was it worth it,

35:52.000 --> 35:54.000
given it has earned you
the contempt of almost everyone

35:54.000 --> 35:55.500
in the room?

35:55.500 --> 35:58.600
Almost everyone?

35:58.600 --> 36:00.966
Who's the exception?

36:01.866 --> 36:03.100
I made a decision

36:03.100 --> 36:07.500
not so long ago not to care
what anyone thinks of me.

36:07.500 --> 36:09.733
It was enormously liberating.

36:09.733 --> 36:13.166
I prefer to live my life
on my own terms,

36:13.166 --> 36:17.233
outside the narrow confines
of polite society.

36:21.333 --> 36:23.666
I highly recommend it.

36:24.933 --> 36:27.800
Then again,
it takes a brave lamb

36:27.800 --> 36:30.233
to wander from the flock.

36:30.233 --> 36:35.566
♪ ♪

36:48.566 --> 36:51.900
(men groan)

36:53.266 --> 36:55.500
You need to roll a four
to win.

36:56.566 --> 36:59.133
(dice rattling)

37:02.933 --> 37:04.766
(men groaning loudly)

37:04.766 --> 37:07.933
TOM:
Wait, what just
happened?

37:07.933 --> 37:10.133
You threw a four.

37:10.133 --> 37:11.500
They lost, you won.

37:11.500 --> 37:13.066
(exhales)

37:13.066 --> 37:14.466
And if I'd not thrown a four?

37:14.466 --> 37:16.833
You'd have paid back
double the stakes.

37:16.833 --> 37:18.000
I need to sit down.

37:18.000 --> 37:19.866
You played admirably, Tom.

37:19.866 --> 37:22.066
You're a worthy opponent,
indeed.

37:22.066 --> 37:23.700
Get this man
a bottle of wine!

37:26.300 --> 37:29.566
(music playing)

37:29.566 --> 37:32.133
ALISON:
I am trying to follow
Georgiana's advice

37:32.133 --> 37:33.233
and be more reserved,

37:33.233 --> 37:35.300
but it is so hard
when I am with him.

37:35.300 --> 37:38.100
Try not to fall too fast,
Alison.

37:38.100 --> 37:39.566
Can't you feel
from my heartbeat

37:39.566 --> 37:42.233
that it's just too late
for such advice?

37:42.233 --> 37:45.966
(piece ends, applauding)

37:50.033 --> 37:51.566
LADY DENHAM:
Edward.

37:51.566 --> 37:54.666
I intend to ask your colonel
to join me for tea tomorrow.

37:54.666 --> 37:57.133
I wish to show him
my brother's medals.

37:57.133 --> 37:58.366
I'm sure he'd be delighted,
Aunt.

37:58.366 --> 37:59.600
Hmm...

37:59.600 --> 38:02.233
And it would also provide
an opportunity for him

38:02.233 --> 38:06.466
to give his unvarnished
impression of you.

38:07.600 --> 38:09.033
Edward...

38:09.033 --> 38:11.400
Might I persuade you
to dance?

38:11.400 --> 38:12.866
Sister, I would gladly...
Not with me.

38:12.866 --> 38:15.133
I'd rather dance barefoot
on broken glass.

38:15.133 --> 38:17.300
Miss Hankins.

38:19.033 --> 38:24.466
(people talking in background)

38:25.766 --> 38:28.100
(music playing)

38:42.300 --> 38:46.266
(music continues)

38:46.266 --> 38:49.900
Which of them is this
designed to humiliate?

38:49.900 --> 38:51.033
Neither.

38:51.033 --> 38:53.333
It's to repay Miss Hankins
for her kindness.

38:53.333 --> 38:55.400
And to see how far
Edward would go

38:55.400 --> 38:59.833
to prove he's a human being.

38:59.833 --> 39:05.066
(music continues)

39:07.966 --> 39:11.533
♪ ♪

39:11.533 --> 39:15.266
(people talking in background)

39:23.100 --> 39:25.200
(chuckles)

39:25.200 --> 39:27.300
Can I interest you
in a nightcap, Mr. Parker?

39:27.300 --> 39:30.000
I have a rather good port wine
in my studio.

39:30.000 --> 39:32.166
Oh, well, I adore port wine.

39:32.166 --> 39:35.700
♪ ♪

39:42.800 --> 39:44.966
Alison?

39:44.966 --> 39:46.000
Thank you, Captain.

39:46.000 --> 39:47.766
I have had the most wonderful
evening.

39:47.766 --> 39:48.766
As have I.

39:48.766 --> 39:50.866
Worthy of Cowper.

39:50.866 --> 39:53.566
Thank you.

39:54.933 --> 39:56.733
Fraser, you must help me.

39:56.733 --> 40:01.966
Miss Heywood, she is a woman
of refinement, poetry.

40:01.966 --> 40:04.033
You know such things.

40:04.033 --> 40:06.233
Please.

40:06.233 --> 40:08.166
Why?

40:08.166 --> 40:12.466
As a friend
and fellow officer, Declan.

40:12.466 --> 40:14.866
(sighs)
(chuckles)

40:14.866 --> 40:16.366
Thank you.

40:16.366 --> 40:17.700
I'll be forever in your debt.

40:17.700 --> 40:21.000
♪ ♪

40:21.000 --> 40:22.166
Miss Heywood.

40:22.166 --> 40:24.433
Thank you for your advice
on military strategy.

40:24.433 --> 40:26.133
I hope it proves useful.

40:26.133 --> 40:27.666
Let me know if you wish
to borrow a cannon.

40:27.666 --> 40:30.233
(laughs):
I'm not sure Mr. Colbourne
would sanction that.

40:30.233 --> 40:32.233
Colbourne, did you say?

40:32.233 --> 40:33.366
Yes.

40:33.366 --> 40:34.333
Why? Do you know him?

40:34.333 --> 40:36.500
Only by reputation.

40:36.500 --> 40:37.533
I bid you a good evening.

40:37.533 --> 40:39.166
Good evening.

40:39.166 --> 40:41.633
♪ ♪

40:46.300 --> 40:51.466
(seagulls squawking)

40:54.433 --> 40:56.000
I wondered if there was anyone
who caught your eye

40:56.000 --> 40:57.333
at dinner last night.

40:57.333 --> 41:01.700
Unlike Alison, I don't swoon
at the sight of a soldier.

41:01.700 --> 41:05.133
It was not a soldier
you were sitting next to.

41:05.133 --> 41:08.566
I maintain my first impression
of Mr. Lockhart:

41:08.566 --> 41:13.066
he's all conceit
and affectation.

41:13.066 --> 41:15.166
I'd hoped you'd find yourself
sitting next to someone

41:15.166 --> 41:17.600
handsome and eligible...

41:17.600 --> 41:19.233
No more talk of marriage.

41:19.233 --> 41:21.233
I beg you.

41:21.233 --> 41:23.333
I've had my fill of suitors.

41:23.333 --> 41:28.433
If any man is to request an
audience, you are to decline.

41:28.433 --> 41:33.066
If and when I marry,
it will be on my terms.

41:33.066 --> 41:35.733
Mine and mine alone.

41:38.933 --> 41:40.966
LENNOX:
I hope you didn't mind

41:40.966 --> 41:44.166
my asking Captain Denham
to join us, milady.

41:44.166 --> 41:47.133
He was as keen to hear about
his late uncle as I am.

41:47.133 --> 41:50.800
Yes, well, Edward has always
taken a very keen interest

41:50.800 --> 41:52.233
in family matters.

41:52.233 --> 41:54.300
LENNOX:
I'm not surprised your nephew

41:54.300 --> 41:56.500
is from such a
distinguished lineage.

41:56.500 --> 41:59.200
These past months,
he has proved himself

41:59.200 --> 42:00.466
an exemplary officer.

42:00.466 --> 42:03.300
Honorable, courageous,
disciplined.

42:03.300 --> 42:06.500
LADY DENHAM:
Yes, so you said,
at the mess dinner.

42:08.100 --> 42:09.133
If I may...

42:09.133 --> 42:11.900
(places cup and saucer down)

42:11.900 --> 42:14.366
I know familial relations
between you have been strained

42:14.366 --> 42:16.100
in the past.

42:16.100 --> 42:18.300
But when he joined up,
Captain Denham spoke

42:18.300 --> 42:19.800
of a desire to atone.

42:19.800 --> 42:22.500
And nothing I've seen since
has caused me

42:22.500 --> 42:24.900
to doubt his sincerity.

42:24.900 --> 42:27.033
LADY DENHAM:
Colonel Lennox,
let me show you

42:27.033 --> 42:29.200
Maximilian's portrait.
(door opens)

42:35.233 --> 42:37.966
I trust you two can be
civil with each other

42:37.966 --> 42:39.833
if I leave you alone.

42:43.366 --> 42:46.466
LADY DENHAM (in distance):
Now, this portrait was painted
when he was 17.

43:05.533 --> 43:07.000
Miss Colbourne and I
are going to look for food

43:07.000 --> 43:09.200
for her snails this afternoon.

43:09.200 --> 43:10.333
Will you join us?

43:14.133 --> 43:16.966
The charms of a simple farm girl
may work on a child,

43:16.966 --> 43:19.600
but they do little
to enchant me.

43:19.600 --> 43:24.133
Nor any potential suitor,
I should imagine.

43:24.133 --> 43:26.200
Hmm, maybe that is why you are
condemned to such a loveless

43:26.200 --> 43:28.300
and lonely life, Miss Heywood.

43:28.300 --> 43:31.766
(inhales):
Well, one of the reasons.

43:33.366 --> 43:36.133
I have known love, Miss Markham.

43:37.433 --> 43:39.433
Hmm.

43:39.433 --> 43:43.633
And let me guess, he ignored
your every simpering advance.

43:43.633 --> 43:46.033
(turns page)

43:46.033 --> 43:49.200
No.

43:49.200 --> 43:50.766
I was loved in return.

43:50.766 --> 43:55.966
But circumstances
conspired against us.

43:55.966 --> 43:58.166
Then he died.

43:58.166 --> 44:02.900
♪ ♪

44:02.900 --> 44:06.966
Miss Markham,
our lives may seem worlds apart,

44:06.966 --> 44:10.366
but I know what it means
to grieve.

44:10.366 --> 44:12.433
♪ ♪

44:12.433 --> 44:14.600
(exhales sharply)

44:17.100 --> 44:21.766
We are nothing alike,
Miss Heywood.

44:23.100 --> 44:25.366
Tell me something.

44:25.366 --> 44:28.600
Your parents.

44:28.600 --> 44:31.466
A happy memory, perhaps.

44:33.400 --> 44:35.566
I...

44:39.300 --> 44:43.300
I used to play for them.

44:43.300 --> 44:46.066
Lively tunes that would make
everyone laugh.

44:48.333 --> 44:51.300
They would sing.

44:54.000 --> 44:55.233
(exhales)

44:55.233 --> 44:58.233
I could play for you.

44:58.233 --> 45:00.600
If you'd like.

45:00.600 --> 45:05.500
My Aunt Lucy's spinet
in the drawing room.

45:05.500 --> 45:07.333
We can unlock it.

45:07.333 --> 45:11.300
I should very much like that.

45:11.300 --> 45:14.966
♪ ♪

45:35.566 --> 45:38.633
Esther, if our aunt
can forgive me...

45:38.633 --> 45:42.100
Well, that remains very much
in question.

45:42.100 --> 45:43.200
I'm sorry,

45:43.200 --> 45:46.933
desperately sorry,
for how I wronged you.

45:46.933 --> 45:50.066
But ever since
my return to Sanditon,

45:50.066 --> 45:53.433
I've done my best to prove
to you that I am reformed.

45:54.566 --> 45:56.366
Does the colonel's word
count for nothing?

45:56.366 --> 45:58.433
I barely know the man.

45:58.433 --> 46:00.500
I know you all too well.

46:00.500 --> 46:04.200
But you're not the same woman
that you once were.

46:04.200 --> 46:06.200
Marriage has transformed you.

46:06.200 --> 46:07.966
You carry yourself
differently.

46:07.966 --> 46:10.566
You have an assurance
that you never had before.

46:10.566 --> 46:13.266
That's because I escaped
your influence.

46:15.500 --> 46:19.100
I don't doubt it.

46:19.100 --> 46:22.133
But the point is,
if you can be

46:22.133 --> 46:24.366
so utterly changed,

46:24.366 --> 46:27.366
is it not possible
that I might be, too?

46:27.366 --> 46:32.833
♪ ♪

46:44.133 --> 46:50.033
♪ ♪

46:51.333 --> 46:53.700
(fallboard clatters,
remains shut)

46:53.700 --> 46:55.866
Why is it kept locked?

46:55.866 --> 46:56.933
You know Leonora.

46:56.933 --> 46:59.766
She will have it destroyed
in an instant.

47:02.366 --> 47:04.733
(lock turns)

47:04.733 --> 47:07.133
(shutter opens)

47:11.000 --> 47:13.200
(playing tune)

47:13.200 --> 47:16.400
(out-of-tune note playing)

47:16.400 --> 47:19.933
Seems it hasn't been played
in some time.

47:19.933 --> 47:21.866
It's a bit out of tune.

47:21.866 --> 47:25.033
My ear is not
refined enough to say.

47:25.033 --> 47:28.733
Perhaps you could play
something.

47:28.733 --> 47:30.633
(begins piece)

47:30.633 --> 47:32.133
(out-of-tune chord plays)

47:32.133 --> 47:33.400
(plays notes hesitantly)

47:33.400 --> 47:35.800
I'm a bit out of practice.

47:35.800 --> 47:42.866
(piece continues slowly)

47:48.700 --> 47:50.833
Louder.

47:52.300 --> 47:56.633
(spinet playing in distance)

47:56.633 --> 48:02.866
(piece continues)

48:13.200 --> 48:14.233
Stop.

48:14.233 --> 48:16.000
(stops playing)

48:16.000 --> 48:17.500
Forgive me, sir, I...

48:17.500 --> 48:18.800
This is locked
for a reason.

48:18.800 --> 48:20.933
Who told you
you could play it?

48:20.933 --> 48:25.366
Augusta, this has your name
written all over it.

48:25.366 --> 48:27.866
No, sir-- it was I.

48:28.833 --> 48:30.733
I asked one of the servants
for the key.

48:30.733 --> 48:33.200
What is the point
in a spinet

48:33.200 --> 48:34.433
if not to be played?

48:34.433 --> 48:38.300
(Leonora shouting)

48:38.300 --> 48:40.566
COLBOURNE:
Leonora, what are you wearing?!

48:40.566 --> 48:43.233
Miss Heywood said a woman
can dress for whatever

48:43.233 --> 48:44.733
suits her purpose.

48:44.733 --> 48:48.800
She says a girl can be whatever
she wants to be.

48:48.800 --> 48:50.366
(door closes)

48:50.366 --> 48:52.633
CHARLOTTE:
I have tried,
Mr. Colbourne.

48:52.633 --> 48:54.733
And like those before you,
you have failed.

48:54.733 --> 48:56.433
No, sir.

48:56.433 --> 48:58.200
I shall not shoulder
that burden alone.

48:58.200 --> 49:00.033
You told me I'm not here
to educate you,

49:00.033 --> 49:02.900
but there is much
you have to learn.

49:02.900 --> 49:05.833
Miss Colbourne lacks a mother
and also a father.

49:05.833 --> 49:07.166
She lost the former
to the grave

49:07.166 --> 49:08.966
and the latter to his work.

49:08.966 --> 49:11.100
And Miss Markham,

49:11.100 --> 49:13.233
were she to let anyone in,
might become a woman

49:13.233 --> 49:14.566
of lively intellect,

49:14.566 --> 49:17.100
ready to step into society,
as you desire.

49:17.100 --> 49:19.266
But who listens to her?

49:19.266 --> 49:21.266
Who even speaks
in this house of silence,

49:21.266 --> 49:23.566
this mausoleum?

49:23.566 --> 49:27.033
So, this may be the last lesson
I teach in this house,

49:27.033 --> 49:29.166
but it is decidedly
the most pertinent!

49:29.166 --> 49:32.133
You wish to leave?

49:33.400 --> 49:34.800
No, but I assumed...

49:34.800 --> 49:37.966
Tomorrow, then.

49:37.966 --> 49:38.966
Same time.

49:38.966 --> 49:45.066
♪ ♪

49:57.033 --> 50:00.700
It seems you owe me
a shilling, sir.

50:07.700 --> 50:10.700
(birds twittering)

50:10.700 --> 50:12.100
Why did you lie for me?

50:15.400 --> 50:17.433
Why did you lie to me?

50:17.433 --> 50:19.300
I wanted you gone.

50:20.366 --> 50:23.566
To be replaced
by another governess?

50:23.566 --> 50:24.700
Then another?

50:24.700 --> 50:28.300
My parents have been replaced.

50:28.300 --> 50:30.733
My home.

50:30.733 --> 50:32.300
My whole life.

50:32.300 --> 50:34.833
Then forge a new life.

50:34.833 --> 50:38.066
A new path.

50:38.066 --> 50:39.933
That is what I'm trying to do.

50:44.833 --> 50:46.466
I didn't lie to you.

50:48.066 --> 50:52.333
I did use to play
for my parents.

50:52.333 --> 50:54.233
We did laugh.

50:54.233 --> 50:57.933
And you shall again.

51:01.200 --> 51:07.200
♪ ♪

51:08.933 --> 51:10.300
(knock at door)

51:10.300 --> 51:12.433
